Airlines Fatalities

Introduction

In this project we are analyzing data collected from 1976 to 2001 about airline fatal accidents by the International Civil Aviation Organization in Montreal , Canada (www.icao.int).

Our goal is to get a good prediction about future fatalitis through a bayesian approach.

Our data is structured with four columns, year, fatal, miles, rate.

Passenger miles are in units of 10111011 and the accident rate is the number of fatal accidents per 10111011 passenger miles.

Posterior distribution

The posterior distribution for is |y(634,26)|y(634,26) and the conditional distribution of y~y~ (the number of fatal accidents in 2002) is Poisson()Poisson().

So to simulate values of y~y~ all we need to do is first generate a realized value form the posterior distribution of as the mean. Iterating this process will generate values of y~y~ from the posterior predictive distribution. What we are doing here is integrating numerically, using simulation, over the posterior distrobution in . We can simulate this easily in R.

theta <- rgamma(1000, 634, 26 )
y.2002 <- rpois(1000,theta)
#hist( y.2002 )
plot( table(y.2002), type="h", lwd=5, lend=2, col=gray(0.5), bty="n", ylab="" )

First model

  for( i in 1:I ) {
    fatal[i] ~ dpois(mu)
    }
    mu ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  }", file="a1.jag" )

a1.par <- c("mu","fatal[27]")

We can now fit a model using JAGS

cat( "model
 {
 for( i in 1:I )
 {
 mu[i] <- exp( alpha + beta*(i-10) ) * miles[i]
 fatal[i] ~ dpois( mu[i] )
 }
 alpha ~ dnorm(0,0.000001)
 beta ~ dnorm(0,0.000001)
 }",
 file="a2.jag" )

The node fatal[27] contains the predictive distribution for the number of fatal accidents in 2002. Its posterior mean is 20.04 (similar to that for the expected number of fatal accidents in 2002) with a standard deviation of 4.864 and 95% interval [11,30] We can plot its distribution.

plot( table(a2.m[,"fatal[27]"]), type="h", lwd=5, lend=2, col=gray(0.5), bty="n", ylab="" )

We can notice from the table of true values bolow that our prediction of 20 for the number of fatal accidents in 2002 was wrong as the right one was 14 but still fits well within the prediction interval of (11,30). Finally we notice also that, since 1976, the rate of fatal accident per air mile flown has decreased becoming ten times lower.

Model comparison throughout DIC index

A good way to select the model that fits best our data, is using the DIC measure. The DIC (deviance information criterion) is a Bayesian criterion for model comparison, defined as:

DIC=D()+2pDDIC=D()+2pD
Where: D()=2logL()D()=2logL(), pD=DD()pD=DD(), is the effective number of paramenters of the model, the larger pDpD the easier the model fits on the data. D=E[D()]D=E[D()], its the mean deviance. is a measure of how well the model fits the data, the larger the worse the fit. D()=D[E()]D()=D[E()]

the basic idea is that the models with smaller DIC should be preferred. Models are penalized both by the value of DD, which favors a good fit, but also by the effective number of parameters pDpD. Since DD will decrease as the number of parameters in a model increases, the pDpD term compensates for this effect by favoring models with a smaller number of parameters.

#Model Comparison
DICmod1 = dic.samples(a1.mod, n.iter=10000, thin=10, type="pD")
DICmod2 = dic.samples(a2.mod, n.iter=10000, thin =10, type="pD")
